"# Appendix C — Solution Shape Guide

Every challenge in this book comes with the same three things: a prompt, an example input/output, and a hint. Your solution — however you write it — should come with the same three things pointed the other way: a summary of what you did, a run that shows it working, and a note on the trade-off you chose.

## The three-part solution

1. **What you did, in one sentence.** Not the code — the shape of the answer. \"I folded over the list.\" \"I built an accumulator and pushed at each step.\" \"I broke it in two by parity.\" One sentence.

2. **A run.** Copy the example input from the challenge. Show the actual output. If it matches, good. If it doesn't, keep working — a solution that produces the wrong answer is not a solution.

3. **The trade-off.** Every solution picks something over something else. Simplicity over speed. Speed over memory. Readability over cleverness. Say which you picked and why. This is the piece that turns a homework answer into an engineering note.

## The four shapes most challenges take

- **Fold** — reduce a list to a single value. ch01, ch07, ch08 lean here.
- **Map+filter** — reshape a list, then drop the parts you don't want. ch02, ch04, ch05.
- **State machine** — a small closure that remembers something between calls. ch03, ch09, ch11.
- **Pipeline** — a chain of verbs where the shape of the data changes at each step. ch06, ch10, ch15.

Most challenges yield to one of these four. When yours doesn't, that's the interesting one — write down what shape it took instead.

## When you fail

ch13 is the whole chapter on this. In brief: the wrong answer is a real fact and worth its own paragraph. Don't erase it. Write down what you thought would happen, what actually happened, and the smallest change that made the difference. That paragraph is worth more than the fix.

## The summit

ch16 asks you to compose several earlier chapters into one program. There is no single right answer. Whatever you build, put the three-part shape above on the outside of it. If someone else reads your solution six months from now and can tell what you did and why, the challenge is complete."
